{
  "answer": "**In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Shair\" (شاعر, Chapter 39 of *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*), the Urdu word *sha'ir* (شاعر, \"poet\") is elevated from a mere literary figure to a vital, empathetic organ of the nation—specifically, its \"seeing eye\" (*deeda-e-beena-e-qaum*, ديدہ بينائے قوم).**[^1][^2]\n\nIqbal uses the metaphor of the nation (*qaum*, قوم) as a living body (*jism*, جسم), with its people as limbs (*aaza*, اعضاء), hands and feet pursuing industry and trade (*san'at ke reh-paima*, صنعت کے رہ پيما), and government as its graceful face (*chehra-e-zeba*, چہرہء زيبائے). Amid this organic whole, the *sha'ir* emerges as the perceptive, colorful voice and visionary eye that keenly senses collective pain: \"When one part aches, it cannot help but cry\" (مبتلائے درد کوئي عضو ہو روتي ہے آنکھ, *mubtala-e dard koi uzv ho roti hai aankh*).[^3][^4]\n\nThis thematizes the *sha'ir*'s profound weight as the nation's conscience and seer—sympathetic (*hamdard*, ہمدرد) to suffering across the entire body, not detached but integral to its spiritual and moral vitality. The poet isn't ornamental but essential, embodying awareness and outcry in the face of communal distress, aligning with Iqbal's broader vision of poetry as a force for Islamic renaissance and self-realization.\n\n(Note: A separate poem, \"Shama aur Shair\" in *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 19, dialogues a candle (*shama*) and poet but doesn't center the *sha'ir*'s national role.[^5])\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 39 \"Shair\" (translation), [para. p-0d5b83](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/39-shair/translation/#p-0d5b83).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 39 \"Shair\" (original), [para. p-56a653](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/39-shair/original/#p-56a653).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 39 \"Shair\" (translation), [paras. p-4562af to p-6afdc8](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/39-shair/translation/#p-4562af).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 39 \"Shair\" (transliteration), full chapter.\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 19 \"Shama aur Shair\" (translation), full chapter.",
